content.text: Good, now let me run the query to compute the percentage of Hamilton's results outside first place since 2010.

input.command:
sqlite3 "/Users/david/workspace/claimdb/test_dbs/formula_1.sqlite" "
SELECT 
  COUNT(r.raceId) as total_races,
  SUM(CASE WHEN res.position > 1 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as outside_first,
  SUM(CASE WHEN res.position = 1 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as first_place,
  ROUND(100.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN res.position > 1 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) / COUNT(r.raceId), 2) as pct_outside_first
FROM results res
JOIN drivers d ON res.driverId = d.driverId
JOIN races r ON res.raceId = r.raceId
WHERE d.surname = 'Hamilton' AND r.year >= 2010;
"

content.text:
So there are 150 total races, 49 first place, 83 position > 1, and 18 NULL positions (likely DNFs). The hint says: percentage = COUNT(raceId where position > 1) / COUNT(raceId where surname = Hamilton). Let me compute exactly per the hint formula:

- Numerator: 83 (races with position > 1)
- Denominator: 150 (all races)
- Percentage: 83/150 = 0.5533 = ~55%

That's not 26%. Let me also check if using only non-null positions changes things:

None of these common interpretations give 26%. The claim says "only 26% of Lewis Hamilton's Formula 1 race results were outside first place" since 2010. The data shows 55.3% (83 out of 150) were outside first place using `position > 1`. Even Hamilton's first-place percentage is only 33% (49/150), not related to 26% either.

The claim of 26% is clearly contradicted by the data, which shows approximately 55%.
